Introduction

Problem Statement

A real estate company plans to purchase properties to rent out short-term as part of their business model specifically within New York City. The real estate company has already concluded that two bedroom properties are the most profitable. However, the company doesn't know which zip codes are the best to invest in.

The problem statement requires to clean, analyze and build a data product with conclusions and results that would identify the zip codes that would generate the most profit on short term rentals within New York City.

Datasets

The two datasets used in the problem are publicly available data from Zillow and AirBnB which are described as below.

  • Cost Data: Zillow dataset that provides us an estimate of value for two-bedroom properties
  • Revenue Data: AirBnB is the medium through which the real estate company plans to lease out their investment property. AirBnB dataset provides data on property listings in New York with details including number of bedrooms,neighbourhood,rent,availability among many others.

Assumptions

  1. 2017 is considered to be the current year(and not 2020). This is because the last available data for cost of properties is up till 2017. The cost calculation does not make use of a forecasting model, due to which 2017 will be considered as present.
  2. 2 bedroom listings are most profitable.
  3. Occupancy rate is assumed to be 75%.
  4. The properties will be rented out throughout the year; unlike AirBnb, which specifies the number of days in an year the property is available for rent.
  5. The field 'smart_location' in AirBnB dataset consists of two comma seperated values. The first value is assumed to be the city. The data also conveys the same for all records. This field is used to populate missing values in the 'city' field.
  6. Number of reviews and high review ratings are a measure of popularity of the property
  7. The investor will pay for the property in cash (i.e. no mortgage/interest rate will need to be accounted for).
  8. The time value of money discount rate is 0%
  9. All properties and all square feet within each locale can be assumed to be homogeneous (i.e. a 1000 square foot property in a locale such as Bronx or Manhattan generates twice the revenue and costs twice as much as any other 500 square foot property within that same locale.) (This is a given assumption. However, based on the data, for listings containing square feet values, the square feet and the price per night are not homogeneous).

Key Features

  1. Generic functions are used for cleaning the cost and revenue datasets with parameters for city ('New York') and number of bedrooms (2) provided in the function call. This is to ensure the data is scalable and ready to use when approaching a new market.
  2. 2017 being assumed as the present date, cost of properties in each zipcode in the cost dataset is computed using exponential moving average (EMA) of 10 years' data. This enables to capture the trend over ten years while assigning more weightage to recent years.
  3. There were 0.77% missing zipcodes in the revenue dataset. The missing zipcodes were computed using Geopy Python client with corresponding latitude and longitude for each listing.
  4. Break Even Time is computed to estimate the number of years the company will take to offset the property cost.
  5. Profit Projections for 10,15,20,25 and 30 years are tracked to estimate the profit generated by properties over time.

New Variable Definitions

  • Cost_Estimate : Cost of a property, computed using Exponential Moving Average of 10 years' data(2007-2017).
  • city_replace : City name used to populate missing values for the field 'city' in the revenue dataset.
  • yearly_revenue : Yearly revenue generated from a listing. The revenue is computed using the formula: price(rent per night) * 0.75(occupancy rate) * 365(the listing is assumed to be available for 365 days).
  • Break_Even_Time : Break Even Time is the time(in years) that will be required for the company to cover its expenses on buying the property. It is computed using the formula : Cost_Estimate/yearly_revenue
  • Year_10, Year_15, Year_20, Year_25, Year_30 : 10,15,20,25 and 30 year Profit Projections for each zipcode.
  • ROI_10, ROI_15, ROI_20, ROI_25, ROI_30 : 10,15,20,25 and 30 year ROI Percentage Projections for each zipcode.
  • ratingscore : ratingscore categorizes the review scores into four categories - Outstanding, Good, Average, Poor (This field is used for visualizing the popularity of zipcodes).
  • Revenue_Category : Revenue_Category categorizes the yearly revenue into High and Low based on median. (This field is used to visualize zipcodes with high/low revenue and high/low break even times).
  • BreakEvenTime_Category : BreakEvenTime_Category categorizes the Break Even Time into High and Low based on median.(This field is used to visualize zipcodes with high/low revenue and high/low break even times).

Data Preprocessing/Munging

Cost Data

The function 'zillow_data_qualitycheck()' is defined to perform data filtering, cleaning and quality analysis on the cost(Zillow) dataset. The function takes the dataset and the city name as arguments.

Data Filtering, Cleaning and Quality Check

  1. Data Filtering : The cost dataset is filtered with the city name argument 'New York'.
  2. Handling missing values : Year-Month columns with significant percentage of missing values are identified in order to exclude them from computing the cost of properties in a zipcode. Year-month fields up till 2004-07 have more than 20% missing values. The trend of missing counts is analyzed over the years and it could be observed that data from 2007-06 to 2017-06 has no missing values. Also, 10 years of cost data would be sufficient to analyze/capture trend and estimate the cost in 2017 (current cost) and hence the columns before 2007-06 are ommitted.
  3. Verifying duplicate occurences and datatypes : Function 'data_checker()' is implemented to identify and eliminate duplicate records and to verify datatypes of fields in order to prepare them for manipulation and analysis.
  4. Trend and Distribution : The trend of the cost of properties is plotted to analyze the distribution of prices across the years for each zipcode. Almost all zipcodes have an upward trend in cost with moderate variability. No skewness or outliers can be observed for the years from 2007-2017. Hence, the 10 year data can be used to estimate the current cost of properties for each zipcode.
  5. Cost Calculation : The cost is calculated using an Exponential Moving Average model. Due to its ability to place greater weight on the most recent data points, it reacts well to recent cost variability and captures the trend while smoothing the cost.

def zillow_data_qualitycheck(cost_data,city):
    #Filtering the data to only consider 'New York' out of all listed cities
    
    #Data subsetting
    cost_Nydata = cost_data[cost_data.City == city]
    
    #Handling missing values
    #Identify columns with missing values
    missingValueColumns = cost_Nydata.columns[cost_Nydata.isnull().any()].tolist()
    #Fetching the historical median price for each year-month and plotting missing value counts for each (up till 2007-05)
    #as there are no missing values in the columns after.
    cost_Nydata_missingcounts = cost_Nydata.iloc[:, 7:141].isnull().sum()
    list_of_years = list(range(1996, 2018))
    average_of_cost_by_years = [cost_Nydata_missingcounts[cost_Nydata_missingcounts.index.str.startswith(str(year))].mean() for year in list_of_years]
    average_of_cost_by_years = [0 if math.isnan(x) else x for x in average_of_cost_by_years]
    
    # Defines the chart font style
    font = {'family' : 'Times New Roman',
        'weight' : 'bold',
        'size'   : 8}

    # includes the chart font style
    plt.rc('font', **font)
    figure(num=None, figsize=(10, 3))
    plt.bar(list_of_years, average_of_cost_by_years, width=0.5, color = 'c', label='legend title')
    plt.ylabel('Average number of missing values',size=12)
    plt.xlabel('Year',size=12)
    plt.title("Average number of missing values per year",size=15)
    plt.show()
    #From the plot, it can be observed that the percentage/count of missing values is decreasing with years. 
    #Count of missing values is almost exponentially decreasing from year 2003 until 2007, after which it is 0
    
    #Identifying columns with more than 20% missing values
    print("Columns with more than 20% missing values")
    missinggt20 = round(cost_Nydata.isnull().mean()*100,2)>20.00
    print(missinggt20[missinggt20].index.values)
    #Though fields from 2004 - 09 TO 2007 - 05 have less than 20% missing values, they still have missing data 
    #due to which they will be omitted from computation of price. 
    #Also 10 years of data(from 2007-06 to 2017-06) should be sufficient to capture trend and calculate price.
    
    #Verifying for duplicate occurences and dropping them in case.
    #Also verifying the types of all data fields to handle any conversions
    #print(data_checker(cost_Nydata))
    
    print('\nPlotting the yearly median cost per zip code...')
    li=[]
    for year in list_of_years:
       li.append(cost_Nydata.filter(regex=str(year)).median(axis=1, skipna=True))

    result = pd.concat(li, axis=1, sort=False)
    list_of_years_named = [str(x) + '_median' for x in list_of_years]
    result = result.rename(columns=dict(zip(result.columns.tolist(), list_of_years_named)))
    result = pd.concat([cost_Nydata, result],  axis=1, sort=False)
    result['RegionName'] = result['RegionName'].astype(str)
    plot_data = result.groupby('RegionName').agg({str(name):'median' for name in list_of_years_named}).reset_index()
    fontP = FontProperties()
    fontP.set_size('xx-small')
    list_of_final_years = list(range(2007, 2018))
    plot_data = plot_data.iloc[:, [0] + list(range(12, 12+len(list_of_final_years)))]

    for ind, row in plot_data.iterrows():
        plt.plot(list_of_final_years, plot_data.iloc[ind, 1:], label = plot_data.iloc[ind]['RegionName'])
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', prop=fontP)
    plt.show()
    
    #It can be observed from the plot that no outliers or significant skewness can be observed from the plot for years
    #2007-2017. 

    #In order to compute a single field that gives a price estimate considering all 10 years,
    #Time series analysis will be used to calculate the moving average of prices over the years. 
    #While mean and median of last 10 years are also viable options, moving average will consider the 
    #trend over time and smooth the pricing. 
    #Also, exponential moving average (instead of simple moving average) is used as it gives more weight 
    #to the recent year-month prices and captures the trend better while being more up to date.
    cost_Nydata_prices=cost_Nydata.iloc[:, 141:262]
    ema_list = []
    for i in cost_Nydata_prices.iterrows():
        exp_moving_average = round(i[1].ewm(alpha=0.1, adjust=False).mean(),2)
        ema_list.append(exp_moving_average[exp_moving_average.index[-1]])
    #Returning preprocessed cost data
    cost_Nydata['Cost_Estimate'] = ema_list
    print(cost_Nydata.head(3))
    #Returning only relevant columns in the dataframe including RegionName, City, CountyName, SizeRank and Cost_Estimate
    cost_data_subset = cost_Nydata[['RegionName','City','CountyName','SizeRank','Cost_Estimate']]
    return cost_data_subset

Data Quality Insights

  1. 101 columns have more than 20% missing values which need to omitted or imputed. Imputing the fields with the median cost would be a better choice as the fields with missing values(year-months before 2004-08 seem to have significant variability.).
  2. There are no duplicate records in the dataset.
  3. The data follows an upward trend with no skewness or outliers from 2007-2017. There is a slight variability from 2007-2009 for a few zipcodes in the distribution but the exponential smoothing average model will be assigning the lowest weight to that time period, thus accounting for its impact on the final cost estimate.

Revenue Data

The function 'airbnb_data_qualitycheck()' is defined to perform data filtering, cleaning and quality analysis on the revenue(AirBnB) dataset. The function takes the dataset and the bedroom count as arguments.

Data Filtering, Cleaning and Quality Check

  1. Data Filtering : The revenue dataset is first filtered to select 24 relevant columns for analysis. Then the data is filtered to select listings that have 2 bedrooms.
  2. Handling missing values
    • Square_feet, weekly_price and monthly_price have the highest missing values. As the missing percentages are significantly high(98.45% missing values in square feet), they are dropped and not imputed.
    • The field 'review_scores_rating' is imputed and the null values are replaced with 0.
    • The missing values in the zipcode were imputed using the Geopy Python client that estimated the zipcodes from latitude and longitude of the listings.
    • The null values in 'city' field is imputed with the first value of column 'smart_location' as it presumably corresponds to the city name, going by the data.
    • The null values in the state are updated as NY.
  3. Verifying duplicate occurences and datatypes : Function 'data_checker()' is implemented to identify and eliminate duplicate records and to verify datatypes of fields in order to prepare them for manipulation and analysis.
In [6]:
#Quality Check - Data Cleaning/Preprocessing- Airbnb Dataset

def airbnb_data_qualitycheck(revenue_data,bedroomcount):
    #Checking columns and their indices for faster retrieval
    #for col in revenue_data.columns: 
        #print(col, "-" ,revenue_data.columns.get_loc(col))
    #Data Subsetting
    #Filtering important columns/fields for analysis
    revenuedata = revenue_data.iloc[:,[0,19,40,41,42,43,45,48,49,51,52,53,55,58,59,60,61,62,77,78,79,80,82,86]]
    #Filtering data to obtain properties with 2 bedrooms
    revenue_data_subset = revenuedata[revenuedata.bedrooms == bedroomcount]
    
    #Handling missing values
    #Identify columns with missing values and respective percentage of missing values. 
    #Only columns with less than 20% missing values will be considered and the rest will be dropped or imputed.
    print(round(revenue_data_subset.isnull().mean()*100,2))
    #It can be observed that square_feet, weekly_price and monthly_price have the highest missing values. As 
    #the missing percentages are significantly high and these are not significant variables for 
    #computing revenue, hence they are dropped and not imputed.
    revenue_data_subset.drop(columns=['square_feet', 'weekly_price','monthly_price'],axis=1,inplace=True)
    #Imputing review_scores_rating and replacing null values with 0
    revenue_data_subset.fillna({'review_scores_rating':0}, inplace=True)
    
    #0.77% missing values for zipcode. Zipcode is detrimental for cost-revenue analysis, hence cannot be dropped.
    #Using geopy Python client to obtain zipcode for missing values by feeding corresponding latitudes and longitudes
    geolocator = geopy.Nominatim(user_agent='zillow-zipcode')
    for i,y in revenue_data_subset.iterrows():
        if(math.isnan(float(y['zipcode']))):
            location = geolocator.reverse((y['latitude'], y['longitude']))
            revenue_data_subset.replace(to_replace = y['zipcode'], value=location.raw['address']['postcode'],inplace=True)
    
    #Updating null values in city with the first value of column 'smart_location' as it presumably 
    #corresponds to the city name based on data
    revenue_data_subset['city_replace']=revenue_data_subset['smart_location'].str.split(',', expand = True)[0]
    revenue_data_subset.city.fillna(revenue_data_subset.city_replace, inplace=True)
    #Updating null values in state as NY
    revenue_data_subset.fillna({'state':"NY"}, inplace=True)
    #Since all missing values have been imputed, verifying whether there are any more missing values
    print("Are there any more missing values? - ",revenue_data_subset.isnull().values.any())
    
    #Handling any duplicate rows in the dataset and verifying the types of all data fields to handle any conversions
    #print(data_checker(revenue_data_subset))
    #Zipcode is object type. Converting into numeric
    revenue_data_subset['zipcode'] = pd.to_numeric(revenue_data_subset['zipcode'] )
    
    #Returning the cleaned revenue data
    return revenue_data_subset

Revenue Calculation

The data is aggregated to calculate revenue. Revenue generated by a listing is dependent on two major factors - occupancy rate(which will be assumed as 75%) and the price per night. Since the property is rented out by the real estate company, it can be assumed that the property will be available for all 365 days in an year. Otherwise revenue must be computed as :- Revenue = price per night x occupancy_rate x available_365

The revenue is calculated using formula: Revenue = price per night x occupancy rate x 365

cost_revenue_mergedf['yearly_revenue'] = cost_revenue_mergedf['price'] * 0.75 * 365

Break Even Time Calculation

Break even time is the time required for the yearly revenue to equal its cost. The break even time (computed in years) will give the number of years it will take for the real estate company to offset the cost. Zipcodes with smaller break even time will indicate earlier and faster profits.

Profits can be estimated in two ways: -

  • Earliest Profit
  • Maximum ROI

Break Even Time will give an estimate of the zipcodes that will be profitable at the earliest. However, early profits do not indicate higher returns over a long term. This is why yearly profit projections are computed for 10,15,20,25 and 30 years to determine return of investment. The ROI projections are computed from 10 year onwards as the minimum break even time is 9 years.

In [10]:
#Calculating Break Even Time

cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Break_Even_Time'] = cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_10'] = - cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'] + cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']*10
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['ROI_10'] = (cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_10']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'])*100
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_15'] = - cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'] + cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']*15
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['ROI_15'] = (cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_15']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'])*100
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_20'] = - cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'] + cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']*20
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['ROI_20'] = (cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_20']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'])*100
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_25'] = - cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'] + cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']*25
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['ROI_25'] = (cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_25']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'])*100
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_30'] = - cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'] + cost_revenue_aggregatedf['yearly_revenue']*30
cost_revenue_aggregatedf['ROI_30'] = (cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Year_30']/cost_revenue_aggregatedf['Cost_Estimate'])*100

Break Even Time vs Zipcode

The plot indicates that even though zipcode 11434 in Queens (the only zipcode with listings in Queens) has very few number of listings, it has the lowest break even time, thus indicating earlier profitability. This is followed by zipcodes 10306, 10303, 10305 and 10304 in Staten Island. This also indicates that Queens and Staten Island being cheap neighbourhoods, the break even time will be less as occupancy rate is assumed to be 0.75 for all neighbourhoods which is unlikely due to the possibility of low demand and listings in Queens and Staten island. Based on break even time, majority of Manhattan zipcodes will give delayed profits due to the occupancy rate again being considered as 0.75, when it could be much higher.

Revenue V/s Break Even Time

The plot distinguishes zipcodes based on revenue and break even time. Ideal zipcodes would be zipcodes with high revenue and low break even time as they would be the most profitable. 10025 and 10036 are high revenue-low break even time zipcodes. Most of the low revenue-low break even time zipcodes such as 11434, 10309, 10304, 10303 belong to Queens and Staten Island neighbourhoods. Such properties have low cost and due to the low demand and location,they have low rents resulting in low revenue. Similarly, most of the high revenue-high break even time zipcodes such as 10003, 10021, 10028 all belong to Manhattan neighbourhood. The high cost causes the high break even time and the high revenue comes from the high rent due to the demand in Manhattan.

Profit Projection for Zipcode

While Break Even time gives the zipcode with earliest profit estimates, it does not indicate the maximum profitable zipcodes. The best approach is to identify the profitable zipcodes over a long term. Since the minimum break even time is 9 years, the profit projections for 10,15,20,25 and 30 years is as computed in the plot.

From the plot, it could be observed that while zipcode 11434 generates profits the earliest(starting from 10 years), the zipcode that generates the highest profit after 20 years is 10025. In another 5 years, at year 25, the most profitable zipcodes are 10025, followed by 10036 and 10022 and the same trend follows up till 30 years. The lowest profit is generated in zipcodes 10013, followed by 10314 and 10309.

ROI Projections based on Cost Estimate for ZipCode

Profits are estimated based on the revenue and cost. The real estate firm may not be willing to invest a high cost as 1.34 million (dollars) for zipcode 10025 that projected the highest profit in 20 and 30 year terms. Probably, the real estate firm may not have the budget to buy expensive properties in zipcodes such as 10025, 10036 and 10022 that give highest profits in 20-30 years but also have the initial cost of more than 1 million(dollars). In order to consider such cases, the ROI Projections based on Cost Estimate for 10,15,20,25 and 30 years is computed. The projected ROIs are percentages.

The zipcodes are sorted in the increasing order of cost. It could be observed that in terms of ROI, the most profitable zipcodes are 11434 with an investment cost of 349K(dollars). It is the 5th least costing zipcode with a very high ROI percentage(more than 200 per cent). This is followed by zipcodes 10306, 10303 and 10305, all of which have very high ROI percentages(more than 180 per cent). The lowest ROI are generated for zipcodes 10013, 10014 and 10023. These are also zipcodes very low profit projections over a 30 year span, so these zipcodes would be poor choices for investment.

Key Findings

  • Zipcode that generates the highest profit after 20 years is 10025. In another 5 years, at year 25, the most profitable zipcodes are 10025, followed by 10036 and 10022 and the same trend follows up till 30 years. The lowest profit is generated in zipcodes 10013, followed by 10014 and 10023.
  • Zipcode that generates the earliest profit(but may not be profitable in the long run) are 11434, 10306, 10303, 10305 and 10304.
  • Zipcode that generates the highest ROI in a 20-30 year span would be 11434, 10306, 10303, 10305 and 10304 with ROI above 150 percent. The lowest ROI is generated from zipcodes 10013, 10014 and 10023.
  • Ideal zipcodes would be zipcodes with high revenue and low break even time as they would be the most profitable. 10025 and 10036 are high revenue-low break even time zipcodes.
  • Manhattan has the highest number of AirBnB listings. High inventory possibly indicates higher demand. Queens has the lowest inventory in New York City in AirBnB.
  • Even though Manhattan is the neighbourhood with highest inventory, zipcode 11215 in Brooklyn has the highest number of listings, indicating more demand for rental stay in zipcode 11215. This is followed by zipcode 10036 in Manhattan, 10003 in Manhattan, and 11217 in Brooklyn.
  • Even though zipcode 11434 in Queens (the only zipcode with listings in Queens) has very few number of listings, it has the lowest break even time, thus indicating earlier profitability. This is followed by zipcodes 10306, 10303, 10305 and 10304 in Staten Island.
  • 1215 in Brooklyn has the highest number of outstanding reviews. This is followed by 11217 (Brooklyn), 10036(Manhattan), 10025(Manhattan), thus indicating high popularity.
  • Among 2 bedroom properties, apartments generate the highest revenue across almost all zipcodes and hence apartments must be invested in for higher profit and ROI.

Results and Conclusions

Profitable zipcodes can be estimated in terms of profit or ROI percent, based on what the real estate firm prioritizes. Also, it is the discretion of the firm to prioritize whether the focus is on generating early profit or maximum profit. Following are the top five best and worst zipcodes for each case, in the order they are listed.

Early Profit (may not be long term)

  • Best Zipcodes : 11434, 10306, 10303, 10305, 10304
  • Worst Zipcodes : 10013, 10014, 10023, 10028, 10021
Maximum Profit (Long term : 20-30 Year span)

  • Best Zipcodes : 10025, 10036, 10022, 11434, 10011
  • Worst Zipcodes : 10013, 10314, 10309, 10014, 10023

Maximum ROI% (Long term : 20-30 Year span)

  • Best Zipcodes : 11434, 10306, 10303, 10305, 10304
  • Worst Zipcodes : 10013, 10014, 10023, 10028, 10021
Note: A good algorithm for occupancy rate will impact the results as occupancy rate is a major determinant in the demand and annual revenue generated from each neighbourhood and zipcode. Occupancy rate algorithm is covered under future scope.

Future Scope

  • As stated in the assumptions, 2017 is considered to be the current date. While exponential moving average captures the trend and is a good solution for calculating the cost for the stated assumption, a time series forecasting model such as the ARIMA (Auto Regressive Integrated Moving Average) model or a model using seasonality such as SARIMA can be used to forecast prices. If the data does not need to use any other independent regressors than price, a model using exponential smoothing and seasonality such as Holt Winters can be used to predict the cost of properties in year 2020.
  • A logic or formula can be derived for Occupancy rate based on data fields such as review ratings, square_feet as occupancy rate is a major determinant in calculating yearly revenue.
  • Zipcode 10013 in the revenue dataset corresponds to two cities - Manhattan and Brooklyn, which is incorrect and may have been caused due to incorrect data entry. The Geopy Python client that was used to compute missing zipcodes could be used to correctly compute zipcodes of all listings.
  • The Geopy Python client takes some time to compute zipcodes. Performance can be improved using optimization tecniques.
